Hydraulic and mechanical properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\,\mathrm{\left[FT/L^{2}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Water viscosity, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[Ns/m^{2}\right]}=\mathrm{\left[Pa\,s\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}\right]},\,k\,\mathrm{\left[L/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Permeability (independent of fluid) and hydraulic conductivity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\rho_{w}g\frac{\kappa}{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are vectors, i.e.
 they are direction dependent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $c\,\mathrm{\left[T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Vertical hydraulic resistance of aquitards or a low-conductive layer, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=d/k_{v}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 the thickness of this layer and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{v}\,\mathrm{\left[L/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 its vertical hydraulic conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $S\,\mathrm{[-]}$
\end_inset

 Elastic storage coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[L^{3}/L^{2}/L\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $S_{s}\mathrm{\left[L^{-1}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Specific elastic storage coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[L^{3}/L^{2}/L\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}\mathrm{\left[L^{-1}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Specific yield 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[L^{3}/L^{2}/L\right]}$
\end_inset

.
 Specific yield is storage from draining pores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\,\beta\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/F\right]}$
\end_inset

 compressibility of water and bulk porous matrix respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/E$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the compression modulus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $E_{w},\,E_{m}\,\mathrm{\left[F/L^{2}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Compression modulus of water and porous medium respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=1/\beta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the compressibility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{w},\,\rho_{s},\,\rho_{b},\,\rho\,\mathrm{\left[M/L^{3}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Density of water, solids, bulk porous medium respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Heat properties and flow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $c,\,c_{w},\,c_{s}\,\mathrm{\left[E/M/K\right]}$
\end_inset

 Bulk heat capacity, heat capacity of water and solids.
 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\epsilon c_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)c_{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda,\,\lambda_{w},\,\lambda_{s}\,\mathrm{\left[E/T/L/K\right]}$
\end_inset

 Bulk, water and solids heat conductance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\epsilon\lambda_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)\lambda_{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\,\mathrm{\left[-\right]}$
\end_inset

 Porosity of the porous medium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 For heat flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}=\frac{\lambda}{\rho c}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 heat conductivity over bulk volumetric heat capacity of water plus medium,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\epsilon\lambda_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)\lambda_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho c=\epsilon\rho_{w}c_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)\rho_{s}c_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 For diffusivity in the context of groundwater flow see under
\series bold
 Aquifer system
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\,\mathrm{\left[-\right]}$
\end_inset

 Retardation, i.e.
 the factor by which transport of mass or heat is delayed relative to that
 of the pore water.
 It is the amount of mass or heat in the water over the total amount of
 mass or heat in the water plus sorbed to/in the grains.
 Hence for heat 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}=\rho_{w}c_{w}\epsilon/\left(\rho_{w}c_{w}\epsilon+\rho_{s}c_{s}\left(1-\epsilon\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 with indices 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 referring to water and grains respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Aquifer system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $q,\,q_{x},q_{y},\,q_{z}\,\mathrm{\left[L/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Specific discharge, which generally is direction-specific (a vector)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $Q\,\mathrm{\left[L^{3}/T\right],\,\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Discharge.
 It can mean the total discharge over the thickness of the aquifer in a
 cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{L^{2}/T}$
\end_inset

 or the extraction or injection of a well, in which case its dimension is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{L^{3}/T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $N,\,\overline{N}\,\mathrm{\left[L/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Net recharge and the time or space average net recharge respectively
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $h\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Phreatic head, in the case of a water table aquifer, the head relative
 to the bottom of this aquifer, i.e.
 the wetted aquifer thickness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Head in semi-confined and confined aquifers, relative to some predefined
 datum, i.e.
 sea level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $s\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Drawdown, or head relative to initial situation (lower case 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $p,\,\sigma_{w},\sigma_{s},\sigma_{e}\,\mathrm{\left[F/L^{2}\right]}$
\end_inset

 Pressure, water pressure, total or soil pressure and effective pressure.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}$
\end_inset

 also used for total pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $H\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Thickness of aquifer.
 Often used only for water table aquifer, sometimes for any aquifer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $D\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Total thickness of aquifer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $kD\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Transmissivity of an aquifer.
 
\begin_inset Formula $kH$
\end_inset

 may be used in an water-table aquifer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $T\,\mathrm{\left[T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Characteristic time of a dynamic groundwater system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Diffusivity.
 For flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}=\frac{kD}{S}$
\end_inset

 for thermal flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}=\frac{\lambda}{\rho c}$
\end_inset

, see under Heat
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Characteristic length or spreading length of a semi-confined aquifer system,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sqrt{kDc}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $kD\,\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 the aquifer's transmissivity and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\,\mathrm{\left[T\right]}$
\end_inset

 the aquitard's vertical resistance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $R,\,R_{0}\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Fixed radial distance to the center of axial symmetric flow system at which
 the head is fixed or zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $LE$
\end_inset

 [-] Loading efficiency, 
\begin_inset Formula $LE=\frac{\beta_{m}}{\epsilon\beta_{w}+\beta_{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $LE+BE=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $BE$
\end_inset

 [-] Barometric efficiency.
 
\begin_inset Formula $BE=\frac{\epsilon\beta_{w}}{\epsilon\beta_{w}+\beta_{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $LE+BE=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Groundwater waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $A\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]},\,B\,\mathrm{[L]}$
\end_inset

 Wave amplitude.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $L\,\mathrm{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

 Width of the groundwater system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 Damping factor of groundwater head wave moving through the aquifer, caused
 by a kind of tide.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\sqrt{\frac{\omega}{2\mathbb{D}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\,\mathrm{\left[T^{-1}\right]}$
\end_inset

 or rather radians per time.
 The angle velocity of the wave.
 Full wave time 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2\pi/\omega$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $T\,\mathrm{\left[T\right]}$
\end_inset

 Cycle time, time of a full wave.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2\pi/\omega$
