\begin_layout Chapter
Reversible groundwater storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the remainder of this syllabus, we will restrict ourselves to reversible
 groundwater storage phenomena, i.e.
 phenomena in which the porous medium is not changed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In groundwater flow systems, three separate forms of storage may be distinguishe
d:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Phreatic storage, which occurs in unconfined aquifers, i.e.
 aquifers with a free water table.
 It is due to filling and emptying of pores at the top of the saturated
 zone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Elastic storage, which is due to combined compressibility of the water,
 the grains and the porous matrix (soil skeleton).
 This storage releases or stores water wherever the pressure changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sometimes, the interface between fresh water and another fluid (be it saline
 water, oil or gas) can provide a third type of storage.
 This works by displacement of the interface, generally between the fresh
 water and the saline water.
 When displacing an interface, the total volume of water in the subsurface
 remains essentially the same, however, the amount of usable fresh water
 may increase (or decrease) at the cost of saline water, and therefore,
 one may consider this storage of fresh water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Phreatic storage (water table storage, specific yield, Sy)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phreatic storage is due to the filling and emptying of pores above the saturated
 zone, i.e.
 above the water table.
 Because it is related to changes of the water table, it is limited to phreatic
 (unconfined) aquifers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The storage coefficient for an unconfined aquifer is called specific yield
 and is denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 It is dimensionless, as follows from its definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{y}=\frac{\partial V_{w}}{\partial h}\label{eq:specific-yield-def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the change of volume of water from a column of aquifer per unit of surface
 area and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h$
\end_inset

 is the change of the water table elevation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

, therefore, is the amount of water released from storage per square meter
 of aquifer per m drawdown of the water table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hydrogeologists, and groundwater engineers alike, often treat specific yield
 as a constant.
 In reality, the draining and filling of pores is more complex and this
 should be kept in mind in order to judge differences of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

 values under different circumstances even with the same aquifer material.
 This will be explained further down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no such thing as a sharp boundary between the saturated and the
 unsaturated porous medium above and below the water table.
 In fact, the water content is continuous across the water table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\emph on
The water table is, by definition, the elevation where the pressure equals
 atmospheric pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because we relate all pressures relative to atmospheric, we may say the
 water table is the elevation where the water pressure is zero (relative
 to the pressure of the atmosphere).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest conceptual model for the zone above the water table is a vertical
 straw or radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 standing with its open end in water.
 Due to adhesion between the water and the straw, the water level will be
 sucked upward in the straw against gravity, thereby reaching an equilibrium
 height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Straw-of-radius-r"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The soil itself may be considered to consist of a dense network of connected
 tortuous pores of small but widely varying diameter that may be fully or
 partially filled with water.
 Due to adhesive forces, pores may even be fully filled above the water
 table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
In pores above the water table the pressure is negative (i.e.
 below atmospheric).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If grains can be wetted (attract water), as is generally the case with water,
 water will be sucked against gravity, into the pores above the water table
 over a certain height.
 This height mainly depends on the diameter of the pores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can immediately compute the equilibrium of the water in the pore.
 We have gravity pulling down the water column reaching above the water
 table, and we have the cohesion force.
 Hence,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho gh\pi r^{2}=2\pi r\gamma\cos\left(\alpha\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 [kg/m 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

] is the density of water, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 [N/kg] is gravity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 [N/m 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

] is the cohesion stress, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 the angle between the cohesion stress and the vertical.
 Hence,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=\frac{2\gamma}{\rho gr}\cos\left(\alpha\right)
\]

\end_inset

which shows that the suction height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

, the inverse radius of the straw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practical situations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is small so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\cos\alpha\approx\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 points is in the direction of the surface tension 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (see figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Straw-of-radius-r"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) where the water surface meets the wall of the straw, we also have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\approx\gamma
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 the surface tension of the water surface, which equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=75\times10^{-3}\mathrm{N/m}$
\end_inset

, see any physical handbook or look it up on Wikipedia.
 Therefore, we can compute the suction head 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 immediately given a pore radius.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
h & \approx & \frac{2\tau}{\rho gr}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerically,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
h & \approx & \frac{150\times10^{-3}}{10^{4}}\frac{1}{r}\\
 & \approx & \frac{1.5\times10^{-5}}{r}\mathrm{\left[m\right]}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we express 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in mm, (using 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset

 to indicate mm), we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h^{*}=\frac{15}{r^{*}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that water in a pore of 1 mm radius may be sucked up over about
 15 mm, and water in a pore with a radius of 0.1 mm over 15 cm and water
 in a pore with a radius of 0.01 mm radius over 1.5 m.
 In reality, the suction may be 50% smaller because of the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 that was ignored here.
\end_layout

