\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Till now, we only considered storage at the water table and gave very simple,
 but practical examples largely ignoring spatial dimensions.
 Spatial dimensions will be dealt with later.
 In this section, we handle the physics of elastic storage and will give
 some interesting everyday examples that are sometimes easily overlooked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elastic storage is the only storage occurring in confined and semi-confined
 aquifers, i.e.
 in aquifers without a water table, meaning aquifers that are completely
 filled with water from floor to ceiling.
 In such aquifers, we have no lowering of the water table whatsoever, unless
 the head is lowered to beneath the ceiling of the aquifer, a case further
 ignored here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, in confined aquifer storage can only result from compression
 of the water and depression of the aquifer.
 The compressibility of the water and the grains themselves is quite obvious,
 but often the less obvious storage is the most important part.
 This is the deformation of the soil skeleton, the bulk matrix or the (bulk)
 porous medium as it is called.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Loading efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To analyze the physics of elastic storage, we start with noting that the
 total load at any depth is carried by the total (vertical pressure) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p\,\mathrm{N/m^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 This total pressure must equal the sum of the vertical grain pressure (the
 so-called effective stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

) and the water pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\sigma_{e}+\sigma_{w}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is indicated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-weight-of-ground-supported-by-sigmaw+sigmae"

\end_inset

