 The brown horizontal beams and the springs in this figure  are imaginary;
 they replace the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $1\mathrm{m^{3}}$
\end_inset

 say) that has been cut out of the aquifer.
 The two imaginary springs have the same properties as the water and the
 porous medium respectively.
 Let us see what happens when the pressure is increased by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case, the volume (or height) 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 and the springs pressures are increased by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The springs have a different stiffness, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}\ne\Delta\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 However, each string will always carry a fixed proportion of the total
 stress.
 Therefore, we may write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\sigma_{w}=LE\,\Delta p
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $LE$
\end_inset

 is this fixed proportion and is called the
\emph on
 loading efficiency
\emph default
.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $LE$
\end_inset

 must obviously lie between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 1 and is fixed for any particular porous medium.
 So if we put a weight, like a layer of sand, on ground surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

