\end_inset

 the change of the barometer pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now assume that the head (i.e.
 the water level) in the piezometer changes by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The change of the water pressure at the bottom of the piezometer then is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\sigma_{w}=\rho g\Delta\phi+\Delta a
\]

\end_inset

But we already know the change of the water pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\sigma_{w}=LE\,\Delta a
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho g\Delta\phi+\Delta a=LE\,\Delta a
\]

\end_inset

and so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho g\Delta\phi & =-(1-LE)\,\Delta a\\
 & =-BE\,\Delta a
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1-LE$
\end_inset

 is called the
\emph on
 barometer efficiency
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $BE$
\end_inset

.
 Just like the loading efficiency, the barometer efficiency varies between
 0 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minus sign indicates that the head in the piezometer declines when the
 barometer goes up.
 This should be obvious as the the water pressure increases by 
\begin_inset Formula $LE\,\Delta a$
\end_inset

 which is a fraction of the barometer pressure, which would cause the water
 level in the piezometer to rise, but at the same time the full barometer
 pressure pushes on the water table in the piezometer, which causes the
 water level to decline accordingly.
 Together, the net effect is a decline of the head in the piezometer by
 
\begin_inset Formula $BE\,\Delta a$
\end_inset

, a fraction of the barometer pressure change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the equivalence of the previous equation couple, it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
BE+LE=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

