\begin_layout Subsection
How much are the loading efficiency and the barometer efficiency when expressed
 in the properties of the water and the porous medium ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the total pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is increased by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p$
\end_inset

, the porous medium is compressed together with the water that it contains.
 Clearly, the increase of the water pressure will also compress the individual
 grains.
 However, sand grains are about 50 times less compressible than water.
 Therefore, the effect of the grains being compressed themselves can be
 safely neglected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the porous medium (the skeleton of grains) itself is
 far less stiff than the grains themselves.
 The porous medium is essentially compressed due to some deformation of
 the grains at the expense of the porosity of the medium.
 In fact, as it turns out, the compressibility of the porous medium is of
 the same order of magnitude as that of the water, so they must both be
 taken into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/compressionAquifer.png
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Compression-of-the-porous-medium"

\end_inset

Compression of the porous medium, while the volume of the grains remains
 unchanged because their compressibility is negligible compared to that
 of both the water and the porous medium.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is compressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 when the pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is increased by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the aquifer to be of infinite lateral extent, so that the only possible
 compression is downward.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V=\Delta H$
\end_inset

, which is the change of the thickness of the considered part of the layer
 that we replaced by the springs in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-weight-of-ground-supported-by-sigmaw+sigmae"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, both springs underlie the same compression 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the water have a compressibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 meaning that a 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}$
\end_inset

 of water would be compressed by the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for each increase of the water pressure by 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,\mathrm{N/m^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, let the porous medium have a compressibility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,$
\end_inset

 meaning that one 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{3}$
\end_inset

 of the porous medium would be compressed by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N/m^{2}}$
\end_inset

 increase of effective stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 These compressibilities, therefore, have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{m^{3}/m^{3}/\left(N/m^{2}\right)}=\mathrm{m^{2}/N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider that the soil was put under an extra total pressure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p$
\end_inset

 causing it to be compressed by the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H/H_{0}=\Delta V/V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the effective pressure increases due to this compression 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\sigma_{e}=-\frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the grains are considered incompressible, it follows that the change
 of pore volume equals the change of the total volume.
 Therefore, for the water we have a relative volume change (= compression)
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 per 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the water pressure increase is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta\sigma_{w} & = & \frac{\Delta V/\left(\epsilon V_{0}\right)}{\alpha}\\
 & = & \frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\epsilon\alpha}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because we have now related both 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 to the relative volume change 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V/V_{0}$
\end_inset

, we also know the ratio between the change of the effective pressure and
 the water pressure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\Delta\sigma_{e}}{\Delta\sigma_{w}} & = & \frac{\epsilon\alpha}{\beta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta\sigma_{e} & = & \frac{\epsilon\alpha}{\beta}\Delta\sigma_{w}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

With this, we can eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

 from the pressure equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta p & = & \Delta\sigma_{w}+\Delta\sigma_{e}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

to obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta p=\left(1+\frac{\epsilon\alpha}{\beta}\right)\Delta\sigma_{w}
\]

\end_inset

And because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}/\Delta p=LE$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
LE=\frac{\beta}{\beta+\epsilon\alpha}
\]

\end_inset

And because 
\begin_inset Formula $BE=1-LE$
\end_inset

 we also have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
BE=\frac{\epsilon\alpha}{\beta+\epsilon\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Specific (elastic) storage coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The specific storage coefficient is the change of volume per unit volume
 of space per unit change of head:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{s}=-\frac{\partial V/V_{0}}{\partial\phi}\label{eq:Ss-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

it is the volume of water released from the porous medium per m of lowering
 of the head 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (a negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 yields a positive amount of water).
 It is also immediately clear that the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{s}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[m^{3}/m^{3}\right]/m=m^{-1}}$
\end_inset

, the volume of water released per 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{m}^{3}$
\end_inset

 of the porous medium per m of head decline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the situation in which we lower the water pressure, for instance
 by extracting water from the aquifer.
 Lowering of the water pressure in no way changes the total pressure.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p=0$
\end_inset

, which yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\Delta\sigma_{w}+\Delta\sigma_{e}\label{eq:deltaSigma_w+deltaSigma_e=0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the amount of water squeezed out of the porous medium changes.
 A lowering of head causes an increase of the effective pressure (grain
 pressure), and, hence, is associated with a compression of the porous medium.
 Therefore, an increase of the effective pressure ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{e}>0$
\end_inset

), reduces the pore volume by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 due to which the same volume of water is squeezed from the porous medium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta V_{pm}=+V_{0}\beta\Delta\sigma_{e}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $pm$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

porous medium 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An increase of the water pressure, would cause a compression of the water
 within the pores 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon V_{0}$
\end_inset

, by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta V_{w}=-\alpha\left(\epsilon V_{0}\right)\Delta\sigma_{w}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total amount of water released equals the volume squeezed out due to
 the reduction of the pore space plus the volume that is generated by expansion
 of the water due to the reduction of the water pressure:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta V & = & -\alpha\left(\epsilon V_{0}\right)\Delta\sigma_{w}+V_{0}\beta\Delta\sigma_{e}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{e}=-\Delta\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

 in this case (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltaSigma_w+deltaSigma_e=0"

\end_inset

), we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta V}{V_{0}}=-\left(\alpha\epsilon+\beta\right)\Delta\sigma_{w}
\]

\end_inset

so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\Delta\sigma_{w}}=-\left(\epsilon\alpha+\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset

now with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\sigma_{w}=\rho g\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 get 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Van-der-Gun-specific-storage"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\rho g\Delta\phi} & =- & \left(\epsilon\alpha+\beta\right)\label{eq:specific-storage-from-soil-and-water-stiffness}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and, therefore
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\Delta\phi}=-\rho g\left(\epsilon\alpha+\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{s}=-\frac{\Delta V/V_{0}}{\Delta\phi}$
\end_inset

, we now have a formula that allows us to compute the specific elastic storage
 coefficient to the physical elastic properties of the aquifer, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, and the water, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{s}=\rho g\left(\epsilon\alpha+\beta\right)\label{eq:specific-storage-as-rho-g-times(epsAlpha+beta)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which, considering that we reduce the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 to the infinitesimally small 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial$
\end_inset

, completes the proof (see equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ss-definition"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{dimension of }S_{s}=\mathrm{\left[\frac{kg}{m^{3}}\right]\left[\frac{N}{kg}\right]\left[\frac{m^{2}}{N}\right]}=\mathrm{\left[\frac{1}{m}\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As often is more practical to write the dimension of gravity 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[\frac{N}{kg}\right]}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[\frac{m}{s^{2}}\right]}$
\end_inset

.
 They are the same, the first can be seen as the force in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by which gravity pulls a mass of 1 kg downward; the second as the acceleration
 a mass of 1 kg would undergo when freely left to gravity to fall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Application (not for exam)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compressibility of water is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\alpha & = & -\frac{1}{V_{w,0}}\frac{\partial V_{w}}{\partial\sigma_{w}}\,\mathrm{\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/F\right]^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx4.4\times10^{10}\,\mathrm{m^{2}/N}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V_{w}/V_{w,0}$
\end_inset

 is the relative change of the water volume.
 There is some dependency on dissolved components, water containing dissolved
 gas, may be up to three times more compressible than water without dissolved
 gas under normal pore pressure (Lyons, William C.
 (2010): Working Guide to Reservoir Engineering; Elsevier).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compressibility of the porous medium is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta=-\frac{1}{V_{T,0}}\frac{\partial V_{T}}{\partial\sigma_{e}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V_{T}/V_{T,0}$
\end_inset

 is the relative change of the volume of the porous medium.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{T}$
\end_inset

 is, the total volume of the considered soil (including its pores).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the effective stress (=grain pressure), i.e.
 that part of the total stress, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, that is not carried by the water pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 The total pressure equals the weight of the overburden, i.e.
 that of the overlying formations including the water that they contain.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}=p-\sigma_{w}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The soil compressibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the gradient of a stress-strain curve (relative volume change as a function
 of effective stress) of a dry soil sample put under increased stress in
 the laboratory, such that side-ward movement is prevented, exactly as it
 is the case in the actual aquifer under uniform vertical stress.
 Unlike water, the compressibility of soil is not necessarily a constant.
 If the soil is put under higher stress than it had ever supported before,
 then it consolidates, meaning that the change of volume is largely irreversible.
 But under lower than historic stresses, a constant compressibility can
 be determined, and truly elastic behavior can be assumed.
 It should be clear, that this compressibility depends on porosity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gun1980"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presented the following relationship between the compressibility of aquifers
 and depth based on laboratory measurements that were carried out by Van
 der Knaap (1959, unfortunately no direct reference).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta=\epsilon\left(3\times10^{-11}+6.6\times10^{-11}z^{-0.7}\right)\label{eq:Van-der-Knaap-aquifer-skeleton-compressibility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 in [km] is the depth below ground surface and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is porosity.
 Then we can apply equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:specific-storage-as-rho-g-times(epsAlpha+beta)"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{s}=\rho g\left(\epsilon\alpha+\beta\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the relation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
