\begin_layout Standard
Let us first derive the partial differential equation, starting with continuity.
 Considering a small slice of an aquifer of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 (cross section) and write its dynamic water budget in terms of flow rates,
 assuming a constant aquifer thickness 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{net in }=\mbox{rate into storage}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
kD\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\right)_{x+\Delta x}-kD\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\right)_{x}+N\Delta x=S\Delta x\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $kD$
\end_inset

 (assumed constant) yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\right)_{x+\Delta x}-\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\right)_{x}}{\Delta x}+\frac{N}{kD}x=\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\rightarrow dx$
\end_inset

 yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}h}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{N}{kD}=\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We ignore the recharge 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 in this course, as we can always superimpose its effect so that with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial^{2}h}{\partial x^{2}}=\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}\label{eqcontinuit-equation-1D-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Further notice that we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(x,t\right)=h\left(x,t\right)-h_{0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the head change relative to the initial situation 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}$
\end_inset

, which may even depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also notice that often 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is used for the head in a water table aquifer, i.e.
 the elevation of the water table and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 for the head in a confined or semi-confined aquifer, i.e.
 where there is not water table.
 In fact, it matters little what symbol is used, as long at its meaning
 is clearly stated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that for 1D groundwater dynamics, we will mostly work with solutions
 of the following partial differential equation where 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the head change or often also the drawdown, especially when dealing
 with groundwater extraction and wells
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}=\frac{kD}{S}\frac{\partial^{2}s}{\partial x^{2}}\label{eq:diffusion-equation-in-s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffusion-equation-in-s"

\end_inset

 is known as the diffusion equation.
 It appears in many scientific fields like like diffusion, dispersion, heat
 conduction, sorption, consolidation, etc.
 Many researchers have derived solutions for this partial differential equation
 for specific boundary and initial conditions.
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $S/kD$
\end_inset

 is called the diffusivity, often written as a thick D, like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

, which always has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

 whatever the scientific application is.
 The diffusivity is the ratio of the ease of the flow (transmissivity) and
 the storage:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{D}=\frac{kD}{S}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of a phreatic (unconfined, water-table) aquifer, the aquifer
 thickness is no longer constant.
 Unfortunately, there are no transient solutions that take a time-varying
 aquifer thickness into account.
 Linearization is then unavoidable, meaning that one has to choose a proper
 average aquifer thickness (or transmissivity) and remain vigilant that
 the head change should remain small with respect to the saturated thickness
 of the aquifer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The partial differential equation can also be viewed in this basic left-hand
 and right-hand parts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
kD\frac{\partial^{2}s}{\partial x^{2}}=S\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

in which the left-hand side describes the flow in the aquifer and the right-hand
 side the storage.
 To readily understand and let sink in the meaning of this partial differential
 equation, it is perhaps easiest to integrate both sides over a distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
kD\intop_{x}^{x+\Delta x}\frac{\partial^{2}s}{\partial x^{2}}dx=S\intop_{x}^{x+\Delta x}\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
kD\left(\frac{\partial s}{\partial x}\rvert_{x+\Delta x}-\frac{\partial s}{\partial x}\rvert_{x}\right)=\left(S\Delta x\right)\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This clearly shows that the left-hand side is the net inflow of a piece
 with length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 (having dimension [L 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/T] or [L 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

/T] per unit length perpendicular to the cross section of the aquifer, hence
 [L 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/T], while the right-hand side equals the storage over the same aquifer
 distance with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 [L 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

/L 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/L] (volume per unit of aquifer surface area per unit of head increase per
 unit of time).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also notice that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}s}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

is the curvature of the head.
 Whenever that is positive, there is an net inflow at the considered location
 originating from the aquifer adjacent to the considered point or infinitesimall
y small section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally notice that we can replace the head change 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 (normally used for (semi-)confined aquifers) by the absolute head 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 (normally used for water-table aquifers).
 This makes absolutely no difference as only the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 play a role in the equation, which are the same.
 Just read 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 as head difference relative to some initial or average condition.
\end_layout

