\begin_layout Subsection
Using characteristic time and length
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution may be more intuitively expressed using characteristic time
 and length.
 The charactersitci time would be the cycle time, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 it takes for one full tide to complete
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega T=2\pi\rightarrow T=\frac{2\pi}{\omega}\rightarrow\omega=\frac{2\pi}{T}\rightarrow\omega t=2\pi\frac{t}{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, we could set a characteristic length of the tide the aquifer to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=\frac{1}{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The envelopes are thus now expressed as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-A\,e^{-\frac{x}{\lambda}}\le s_{x,t}\le+A\,e^{-\frac{x}{\lambda}}
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 now is the length over which the maximum amplitude declines by a factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $e\approx2.3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation with the length over which the amplitude declines by exactly
 a factor 2 is easily derived
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e^{-\frac{x+\Delta x}{\lambda}} & =0.5e^{-\frac{x}{\lambda}}\\
-\frac{x+\Delta x}{\lambda} & =\ln0.5-\frac{x}{\lambda}\\
\Delta x & =\left(\ln2\right)\,\lambda\\
\Delta x & \approx0.69\,\lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As always when we have an exponentially declining relationship, we can define
 a half-time or half-length.
 That halftime or half-length is always 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(2\right)\approx69\%$
\end_inset

 of the characteristic time of characteristic length, i.e.
 the time or length in which the exponent declines by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e\approx2.3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic length of the tidal wave in the aquifer is, therefore
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=\frac{1}{a}=\sqrt{\frac{2}{\omega}\frac{kD}{S}}=\sqrt{\frac{T}{\pi}\frac{kD}{S}}
\]

\end_inset

and the half-length is just 69% of this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Filling in the characteristic length and time gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{x,t}=A\,e^{-\frac{x}{\lambda}}\sin\left(2\pi\frac{t}{T}-\frac{x}{\lambda}+\theta\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one wishes to express all terms within the argument of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin$
\end_inset

 in terms of the full tidal cycle, one would write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{x,t}=A\,e^{-\frac{x}{\lambda}}\sin\left(2\pi\left(\frac{t}{T}-\frac{x}{2\pi\lambda}+\frac{\theta}{2\pi}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This directly shows that the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2\pi\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the length of a full wave in the subsurface, and, therefore, the expression
 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\lambda/T$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the wave in the subsurface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\frac{2\pi\lambda}{T}=\frac{2\pi}{T}\sqrt{\frac{T}{\pi}\frac{kD}{S}}=\sqrt{\frac{2\times2\pi}{T}\frac{kD}{S}}=\sqrt{\frac{2\times2\pi}{2\pi}\omega\frac{kD}{S}}=\sqrt{2\omega\frac{kD}{S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\frac{2\pi\lambda}{T}=\omega\sqrt{\frac{2}{\omega}\frac{kD}{S}}=\frac{\omega}{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is, what we already derived in paragraph 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par:What-is-the-velocity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "par:What-is-the-velocity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
