 thinking in terms of cycle time and characteristic length is easier for
 the human mind and can be immediately translated to the field situation,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and the damping and delay factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 really provide far little inspiration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fluctuations of temperature in the subsurface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For heat conduction in the subsurface, the same partial differential equation
 (also called
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion equation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) applies if we replace head change by temperature change.
 The only thing that changes is the so-called diffusivity 
\begin_inset Formula $kD/S$
\end_inset

.
 The ease of flow, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $kD$
\end_inset

 with groundwater flow, is now replaced by the heat conduction 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\,\mathrm{\left[W/m\right]=\left[\left(\left(E/T\right)/L^{2}\right)/\left(K/L\right)\right]=\left[E/\left(TKL\right)\right]}$
\end_inset

 and the storage is replaced by the heat capacity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho c\,\mathrm{\left[E/L^{3}/K\right]}$
\end_inset

.
 The dimension is again 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\left[L^{2}/T\right]}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{D=}\frac{\lambda}{\rho c}\,\mathrm{\left[\frac{E/\left(TKL\right)}{E/\left(KL^{3}\right)}\right]=\left[\frac{L^{2}}{T}\right]}
\]

\end_inset

Notice that in the dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 = energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 = time, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 = length, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 = temperature (from Kelvin).
 Because both the heat conduction and the heat capacity consist of a contributio
n from both the water and the grains (solids) of the aquifer, we can compute
 them as a porosity-weighted combination of these contributions.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 for porosity we then have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda & = & \epsilon\lambda_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)\lambda_{s}\\
\rho c & = & \epsilon\rho_{w}c_{w}+\left(1-\epsilon\right)\rho_{s}c_{s}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\,\mathrm{\left[M/L^{3}\right]}$
\end_inset

 is density and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\,\mathrm{\left[E/\left(MK\right)\right]}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 heat per kg solids per degree kelvin (= degree Celsius).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heat capacity of saturated sandy soils is about 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3\,\mathrm{W/m/K}=3\,\mathrm{J/s/m/K}$
\end_inset

.
 The specific heat capacity of water is 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{w}=4018\,\mathrm{J/kg/K}$
\end_inset

 and that of sand grains 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}\approx800\,\mathrm{J/kg/K}$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{s}\approx2650\,\mathrm{kg/m^{3}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\approx35\%$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho c=2.85\times10^{6}\,\mathrm{J/m^{3}/K}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusivity then becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{D}=\frac{\lambda}{\rho c}=\frac{3}{2.85\times10^{6}}=1.06\times10^{-6}\,\mathrm{m^{2}/s}=0.091\,\mathrm{m^{2}/d}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From which we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\sqrt{\frac{\omega}{2\mathbb{D}}}=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{T\mathbb{D}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these values, one can compute between what values the temperature varies
 at any given depth as a function of the cycle time.
 For instance, the temperature fluctuation due to daily, weekly, monthly
 or yearly temperature fluctuations at ground surface.
 These envelopes are defined by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{mean}-A\,\exp\left(-az\right)\le temp\le T_{mean}+A\,\exp\left(-az\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 [K] the temperature fluctuation amplitude at ground surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The monthly temperature in the Netherlands varies between 3.1 
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C in January and 17.9 
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C in July.
 The yearly amplitude is thus 7.4 
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C; the year mean temperature being 10.5 
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C.
 Using this, we can compute the temperature envelopes, that is, the lowest
 and highest temperatures between which the actual temperature will vary.
