\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, we discussed the effect of sinusoidal variation
 of the level of a surface water that is in direct contact with a confined
 or unconfined aquifer.
 In this chapter, we'll discuss the same hydrological setting, but in which
 the surface water level changes suddenly by a fixed amount.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basins of half-infinite lateral extent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we consider a confined aquifer in direct contact with surface water
 as was done in the previous section.
 The situation is depicted in figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:One-dimensional-groundwater-basin-rise-a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The aquifer thickness, transmissivity and storage coefficient are everywhere
 the same.
 The aquifer is half-infinite, which means that its right end extends to
 infinity.
 We consider the aquifer as confined, because we will assume that its thickness
 is the same everywhere and stays so.
 This is required only to allow a closed analytical solution for the time-depend
ent groundwater flow.
 There are no time-dependent closed analytical solutions for water-table
 aquifers in which the transmissivity varies along with the head and, therefore,
 with time.
 We further assume the aquifer being in direct contact with the surface
 water.
 This implies that there is no hydraulic resistance of any kind between
 the surface water and the aquifer.
 This assumption keeps the analysis simple.
 However, solutions exist that take hydraulic resistance between the surface
 water and the aquifer into account as outlined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bruggeman1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but are beyond this course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We present here a basic analytical solution, which describes the change
 of head (and flow) caused by a sudden change of the surface-water level
 by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 [m].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the confined case we use the elastic storage coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=DS_{s}$
\end_inset

 and in the unconfined case we use the specific yield, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

.
 In cases where we consider unconfined aquifers, the effective thickness
 of the aquifer changes along with the water table, and, therefore, also
 with the head.
 However, as long as the change of head is small compared to the thickness
 of the aquifer, we may still apply the solution in practice and accept
 the small error caused by the assumption of constant thickness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially, the head is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'$
\end_inset

