Higher-order solutions (not for exam)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous well-known basic solution is the first of an infinite series
 of solutions of the same partial differential equation but for different
 boundary conditions, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(0,t\right)=a\,t^{n/2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 The solution given above is for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entire series of solutions is given is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Carslaw1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bruggeman1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but can be more conveniently written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=A\,t^{n/2}\frac{\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,u}{\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,0}\mbox{, with }u=\sqrt{\frac{x^{2}S}{4kDt}}
\]

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,u$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

 repeated integral of the complementary error function (Section 7.2 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Abramowitz1972"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 A number of these functions is shown in figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:-higher-order-erfc-functions"

\end_inset

.
 These higher order repeated integrals are not in Abramowitz and Stegun
 (1964) but can be easily computed using a recursive expression given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,z=\intop_{z}^{\infty}\mbox{i}^{n-1}\mbox{erfc}\left(\zeta\right)d\zeta
\]

\end_inset

 with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{i}^{0}\mbox{erfc}\,z=\mbox{erfc}\,z
\]

\end_inset

and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{i}^{-1}\mbox{erfc}\,z=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}e^{-z^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher order functions may be computed by the following recursive relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,z=\frac{-z}{n}\mbox{i}^{n-1}\mbox{erfc}\,z+\frac{1}{2n}\mbox{i}^{n-1}\mbox{erfc}\,z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By applying Darcy's law, we find the discharge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\left(x,t\right)=\frac{\sqrt{kDS}}{2\sqrt{t}}A\,t^{n/2}\frac{\mbox{i}^{n-1}\mbox{erfc}\,u}{\mbox{i}^{n}\mbox{erfc}\,0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(0,t\right)=At^{n/2}$
\end_inset

 we could write 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(0,t\right)=Bt^{n/2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 This is more convenient when we like to specify the flow instead of the
 head.
 If we just write 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sqrt{kDS}}{2\sqrt{t}}A=B$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q\left(x,t\right)=B\,t^{n/2}\frac{\mathrm{i^{n-1}erfc}\,u}{\mathrm{i^{n}erfc}\,0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and at the same time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=\frac{2\sqrt{t}}{\sqrt{kDS}}B\,t^{n/2}\frac{\mathrm{i^{n}erfc}\,u}{\mathrm{i^{n}erfc}\,0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A basic solution is obtained by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(0,t\right)=B$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 In that case, the head at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 declines according to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

.
 When the discharge increases linearly, the head at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 changes according to 
\begin_inset Formula $t\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, when the drawdown is constant at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0,$
\end_inset

 the discharge is inversely proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

 and when the head at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 rises linearly with time, the discharge increases according to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

.
