\begin_layout Subsection
Superposition in time, half-infinite aquifer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a half-infinite aquifer in direct connection with surface water
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 The analytical solution for the change of the groundwater head 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 that is caused by a sudden change of the surface water level by an amount
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, which was given before :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=A\,\mathrm{erfc}\sqrt{\frac{x^{2}S}{4kDt}}\mbox{, with }t\ge0\mbox{, where }s\left(x,t\right)=0\mbox{ for }t<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The head change 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 due to an arbitrary sudden change of the surface-water level by an amount
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 happening at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by superposition as usual.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as an event index, we then get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left\{ dA_{i}\,\mathrm{erfc}\sqrt{\frac{x^{2}S}{4kD\left(t-t_{ci}\right)}}\right\} \mbox{, with }t\ge t_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each term is nonexistent, hence zero, for 
\begin_inset Formula $t<t_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The surface-water level at any time is 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(0,t\right)=\sum_{1}^{N}dA_{i}\mbox{, with }t>t_{ci}$
\end_inset

, because each sudden change of water level is supposed to last forever
 after it happened at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{ci}$
\end_inset

.
 This way, one can compute the head change and, of course, the flow in an
 aquifer due to an arbitrary variation of the surface water level at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, if the surface water would vary continuously, like one or more
 
\begin_inset Formula $sine$
\end_inset

 functions, one would rather use the solution for a sine boundary head to
 simplify the computations.
 Even a combination is possible, because superposition applies.
 Notice that the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in the expression above is the simulation time and will be represented
 in the computer by an array of times at some arbitrary constant interval,
 while the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{ci}$
\end_inset

 the
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

change
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-time will be a series of times at which the surface-water level at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 changes.
 The values 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{ci}$
\end_inset

 are independent of the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 values, and the number of change times is is usually much less than the
 number of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will simply compute the head due to the sudden head change 
\begin_inset Formula $dA_{i}$
\end_inset

 happening at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{ch_{i}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t>t_{ci}$
\end_inset

 and add this to the head changes already computed for earlier times.
\end_layout

