\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Confined-groundwater-basin-left-rise"

\end_inset

 shows a groundwater basin with a constant transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $kD$
\end_inset

 and storage coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 It has a width 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and is bounded on either side by surface water in direct contact with the
 confined aquifer.
 The water level at the left changes suddenly by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 How can we solve this, given the solution for the half-space (i.e.
 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 runs from 0 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

) that we already have?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The answer is: by superposition by using mirror “ditches”.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for the half-space has been shown before
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=A\,\mathrm{erfc}\left(x\sqrt{\frac{S}{4kDt}}\right)\mbox{, where }x\ge0\mbox{, and }t>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this solution will cause the head at point 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to start rising after some time, while in reality the head should remain
 0 at point B.
 How wan we deal with this mathematically?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we forget the surface water at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=B$
\end_inset

, but instead assume a ditch at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to the right of point B, in which the water level was suddenly lowered
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 m (i.e.
 changed by an amount - 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

), then the rising an point B due to the ditch at 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 would be exactly counterbalanced (neutralized) by the decline in point
 B due to the ditch at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to the right of point B.
 As a consequence of both, the head at point B remains zero, which is exactly
 the desired effect.
 In this case, we have one mirror ditch with opposite head change at distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to the right of point B.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this one mirror ditch does not solve the whole problem, because
 after some more time, it will cause the head at point A to start declining,
 and so the head at point A would not remain fixed at the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 m.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compensate for that, we need another mirror ditch at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $2L$
\end_inset

 to the left of point A with opposite head change compared to to the first
 mirror ditch.
 But this head change at 
\begin_inset Formula $2L$
\end_inset

 left of point A will cause the head at 
\begin_inset Formula $2L$
\end_inset

 to the right of point B to change over time.
 This requires a mirror ditch at 
\begin_inset Formula $4L$
\end_inset

 to the left of point A to neutralize this effect.
 And so on.
 We will, therefore, end up with an infinite number of mirror ditches just
 to make sure that boundary conditions at both sides of our initial basin
 are kept that their desired values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
