\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Long-term-drainage-behavior-drainage"

\end_inset

Long-term drainage behavior, characteristic drainage time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kraaijenoff-van-der-Leur-Verruijt"

\end_inset

 looks complicated at first, but it can be broken down to yield useful and
 practical insights pertaining to the dynamic characteristics of draining
 groundwater basins.
 For that purpose, we analyze the expression under the summation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $2j-1$
\end_inset

 is just the series 
\begin_inset Formula $1,3,5,7,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-1\right)^{2j-1}=+1,-1,+1,-1,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 Next, we have a product of a cosine and an exponent.
 The cosine will fluctuate between -1 and +1 and it only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then notice the exponent, which only depends on time.
 For simplicity write it as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp\left[-\left(2j-1\right)^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\frac{b^{2}S}{kD}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 may thus be regarded as a characteristic time of the drainage.
 The exponent terms in the series now become
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp\left(-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right),\,\exp\left(-9\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right),\,\exp\left(-25\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right),\,\dots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{t}{T}>0$
\end_inset

, the second and higher terms will finally become much smaller than the
 first and may, therefore, be neglected when 
\begin_inset Formula $t>t_{n}=nT$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 needs to be estimated.
 So let us see when the second term becomes much less than the first one,
 so that only the first term matters and we can neglect all higher terms.
 Therefore, compare the first term with the second and demand that it's
 much larger than the second:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp\left(-\pi^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)\gg\exp\left(-9\pi^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)
\]

\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp\left(-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)=G\,\exp\left(-9\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is just a large positive number.
 We may choose 
\begin_inset Formula $G=100$
\end_inset

, which means, we neglect all higher terms, when the first term is at least
 100 times a large as the second.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the logarithm at both sides of the equal-sign yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}=\ln G-9\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}
\]

\end_inset

Hence, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
8\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}=\ln G
\]

\end_inset

so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{t}{T}=\frac{\ln G}{8\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}}=\frac{\ln100}{8\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}}\approx0.23
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This way, for the chosen value of 
\begin_inset Formula $G=100$
\end_inset

, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.23T$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we conclude that all higher terms are negligible when 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0.23\,T$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, we could also have chosen another large value of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, but the outcome would not be much different because 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is under the logarithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that when 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0.23T$
\end_inset

 the expression given above reduces to only one term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(x,t\right)=A\frac{4}{\pi}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\frac{x}{b}\right)\exp\left(-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)\mbox{, with }t>0.23T\mbox{, and }T=\frac{b^{2}S}{kD}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a simple-to-understand expression.
 It is a cosine that only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, not on time, with its top equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4}{\pi}A$
\end_inset

 in the center where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and zero where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm b$
\end_inset

.
 This cosine-shaped groundwater mound gradually declines according to the
 exponent that only depends on time, not in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An exponential decline can always be characterized by its so-called halftime.
 The halftime is the time in which the head reduces by a factor 0.5.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases by one halftime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{50\%}$
\end_inset

, the head 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\times s\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain this halftime, just write down mathematically that half the head
 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is obtained at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\Delta t_{50\%}$
\end_inset

.
 So literally
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.5\exp\left(-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}\right)=\exp\left(-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t+\Delta t_{50\%}}{T}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Taking the logarithm on both sides yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln0.5-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t}{T}=-\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{t+\Delta t_{50\%}}{T}
\]

\end_inset

and so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\ln0.5 & = & -\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2}\frac{\Delta t_{50\%}}{T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and, therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Delta t_{50\%}}{T}=\left(\frac{2}{\pi}\right)^{2}\ln2\approx0.28
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t_{50\%}\approx0.28T\mbox{, where }T=\frac{b^{2}S}{kD}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that when time progresses by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{50\%}=0.28T$
\end_inset

, the drawdown is halved (under the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0.23T$
\end_inset

 when all higher terms can be neglected).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result allows us to immediately compare the halftimes of the free drainage
 of groundwater basins of widely different sizes and with widely different
 aquifer properties.
 Let the size of the basin be expressed by its representative half-width
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, when a groundwater basin does not have has the shape of a long
 strip bounded by two straight canals, one should estimate a reasonable
 half-width based on the distance from the water divide to its drainage
 base, be it ditches, canals, streams, lakes, rivers or the coast.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Charactersitic-times-of-various-groundwater-basins"

\end_inset

 gives the characteristic time 
\begin_inset Formula $T=b^{2}S/kD$
\end_inset

 and the halftime 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{50\%}=0.28T$
\end_inset

 for some groundwater basins.
 This table illustrates, that different groundwater basins that may have
 similar transmissivities and storage coefficients, may still have extremely
 large differences in half times or characteristic times.
 Especially the effect of the width of the basins, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, is large because it works to the power 2 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T=b^{2}S/kD$
\end_inset

.
 This way, a simple meadow or arable field in the Netherlands bounded between
 two ditches just 100 m apart may have a halftime in the order of one day,
 but large systems, notably deserts, like the Kalahari may have a halftime
 in the order o 10000 years.
 This implies that the small meadow in the Netherlands, will hardly remember
 the rain shower that fell one week ago, while the Kalahari is still draining
 the water that it collected during previous wet episodes may thousands
 of years ago, like the last ice age.
 Recent research with respect to the world's largest aquifer, the Nubian
 sandstone, showed that this aquifer, which extends over much of Sudan,
 Egypt and Libya, may be regarded as a water-table aquifer that is still
 slowly draining the water that it collected during wet episodes when the
 Sahara was still wet (especially between the beginning of the Holocene
 era until about 4600 years ago, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Powell2015,Voss2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and that the current oases represent the last remains of the water table
 reaching above ground surface, and which was much higher thousands of years
 ago.
\end_layout

