\begin_layout Standard
To allow an analytical solution for a transient groundwater problem to be
 found, the governing partial differential equation is linearized before
 solving it.
 Superposition can then be applied using the solutions of the linearized
 partial differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Superposition allows us to add up an arbitrary number of different solutions
 to the same groundwater system in order to handle more complex situations.
 When the underlying governing partial differential equation is linear,
 the effect of individual wells remain completely separated from effects
 of other factors or boundary conditions.
 This implies that precipitation and evaporation play no role when it comes
 to computing the changes of the groundwater heads and flows caused by wells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This simplification may fail when the groundwater system does not obey the
 assumptions that underlie our partial differential equation.
 This is the case, for example, when plant evaporation is reduced in a
\series bold
 nonlinear
\series default
 fashion by the drawdown of the water table.
 One should keep such exceptions in mind when solving practical problems
 and stay aware of the limitations to the calculation methods and formulas
 applied.
 Of course, the same is true when applying groundwater models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Overview-of-the-groundwater-well-solutions"

\end_inset

 shows the most important groundwater-well solutions.
 Only the first one in the table deals with a water-table aquifer; all other
 well solutions require the transmissivity to be constant.
 To use these solutions for water-table aquifers, the drawdown must remain
 small compared to the wet aquifer thickness; it may not change by more
 than say 20% of the original aquifer thickness.
 However, one may often overcome such conditions by using a proper average
 for the aquifer thickness.
 The water-table solution in the table depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}-H^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this can be converted into a product of the drawdown and the
 aquifer thickness as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h^{2}-H^{2}=\left(h-H\right)\left(h+H\right)\approx2sH=2sD\label{eq:h2-H2=2sH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}-H^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the first solution by 
\begin_inset Formula $2sH$
\end_inset

 one obtains the second.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:h2-H2=2sH"

\end_inset

 also gives a clue with respect to the accuracy of using a confined-aquifer
 solution for the water-table case, which we will often do in practice.
 It requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $h+H\approx2D$
\end_inset

.
 A head change of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

