\begin_layout Section
Theis and Hantush wells in an infinite aquifer with constant transmissivity
 and storativity; the governing partial differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1935, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TheisC1935"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 published a new solution for the dynamic change of head 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 [m] caused by a well that, at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, begins pumping at a constant rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\,\mathrm{[L^{3}/T]}$
\end_inset

 from an infinite aquifer having uniform transmissivity 
\begin_inset Formula $kD\,\mathrm{[L^{2}/T]}$
\end_inset

 and storativity 
\begin_inset Formula $S\,\mathrm{[-]}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution by Theis has been a major breakthrough in groundwater hydrology.
 For the first time, it became possible to analyze the dynamics of the heads
 and flows caused by extracting wells.
 Before Theis, only steady-state flow solutions for the groundwater flow
 to wells existed, which very much limited possible analyses of actual pumping
 regimes.
 According to Theis, when a well pumps from an aquifer of infinite extent,
 all water must come from storage; there are no extra sources of the extracted
 water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, 20 years layer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hantush1955"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 developed an analytical solution for the flow to a well in a semi-confined
 aquifer.
 The only difference between the two being that with Hantush, the water
 would not only come from storage from the aquifer itself, but also from
 leakage through an overlying (and or an underlying) aquitard in proportion
 to the drawdown caused by the well.
 This solution also largely extended the possible cases that were amenable
 to analyses.
 Contrary to the Theis-solution, the Hantush solution does approach a steady
 state within a limited time.
 Both solutions are mathematically similar, in fact, the Theis solution
 is a special case of the more general Hantush solution; the Theis solution
 is the Hantush solution for the case that the vertical hydraulic resistance
 of the aquitard 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\frac{d}{k'}$
\end_inset

 [T] (with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\,\mathrm{[L]}$
\end_inset

 the thickness of the aquitard and 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\,\mathrm{[L/T]}$
\end_inset

 its effective vertical conductivity) is infinite.
 Note that the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is [T], i.e.
 time.
 The flow and drawdown caused by extracting from a well in an infinite aquifer
 must be axially symmetric.
 figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pde_axial_flow_to_well"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the general situation in cross section.
 A well with a well radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 is extracting a constant flow 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}\,\mathrm{[L^{3}/T]}$
\end_inset

.
 The aquifer is semi-confined; so there is exchange of water through the
 overlying aquitard with resistance 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 [T] with water on top of that layer with a constant water level 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 All water levels or heads are with respect to an arbitrary datum (reference
 elevation) as indicated.
 The leakage at any 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\frac{h_{0}-h_{r,t}}{c}$
\end_inset

 [L/T].
 The head in the aquifer is denoted by the curved lines.
 During the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 the head increases from 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{r,t}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{r,t+dt}=h_{r,t}+\frac{\partial h_{r,t}}{dt}dt$
\end_inset

.
 Please watch the signs.
 It is clear that when we extract water from the well, the heads will decline
 and the flows designated in the figure  are directed towards the well.
 However, they are drawn in the opposite direction, the direction in which
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is positive and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is positive.
 This facilitates somewhat the derivation, it only has an effect on where
 we will have minus signs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The governing partial differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start the derivation using small discrete values for the distance difference
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta r$
\end_inset

 and the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, which later on will be reduced to the infinitesimal values 
\begin_inset Formula $dr$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Furthermore let 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 be the flow in the middle of our time step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the water budget for a ring between 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r+\Delta r$
\end_inset

 surrounding the well expressed in rates.
 The water budget in terms of rates for the ring then is as follows (using
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 for the head):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{rate of inflow from the right}$
\end_inset

 + 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ rate of inflow from the left}$
\end_inset

 = 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ rate of leakage to adjacent layer}$
\end_inset

 + 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ rate of storage}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\pi\left(r+\Delta r\right)kD\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r+\Delta r}-2\pi rkD\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r}=2\pi r\Delta r\frac{h-h_{0}}{c}+2\pi r\Delta rS\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\pi rkD\left(\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r+\Delta r}-\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r}\right)+2\pi\Delta rkD\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r+\Delta r}=2\pi r\Delta r\frac{h-h_{0}}{c}+2\pi r\Delta rS\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi r\Delta r$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $kD$
\end_inset

 yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r+\Delta r}-\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r}}{\Delta r}+\frac{1}{r}\left(\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}\right)_{r+\Delta r}=\frac{h-h_{0}}{kDc}+\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

Taking the limit for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta r\rightarrow dr$
\end_inset

 yields the partial differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}h}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial h}{\partial r}=\frac{h-h_{0}}{kDc}+\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may set 
\begin_inset Formula $s=h-h_{0},$
\end_inset

 showing that the solution depends on the difference between the head in
 the aquifer and that in the adjacent layer.
 Therefore, our final partial differential equation is in terms of the head
 difference with the constant head in the adjacent layer becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial^{2}s}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial s}{\partial r} & =\frac{s}{\lambda^{2}}+\frac{S}{kD}\frac{\partial s}{\partial t}\mbox{, with }\lambda=\sqrt{kDc}\label{eq:PDF-Hantush}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This partial differential equation is valid for axial flow in a semi-confined
 aquifer, and therefore, also for the Hantush (leaky) situation.
 It should be immediately clear that for 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 when the aquitard becomes impervious, turns into an aquiclude, the term
 
\begin_inset Formula $s/\lambda^{2}$
\end_inset

 drops out.
 This then yields the partial differential equation that is valid for the
 Theis situation.
 Hence, the Theis situation is a special case of the Hantush situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should further be clear from this derivation that the partial differential
 equation is a water budget on infinitesimal scale.
 The left-hand side tells us how much the net flow of water is that flows
 into one meter of the the ring (not out of the ring, because in the last
 but one equation above we changed the sign), while on the right-hand side
 of the equal sign we have the terms that quantify where this net inflow
 goes.
 The first term to the right gives the part that flows into storage, and
 the second term to the right quantifies the leakage lost to the adjacent
 layer.
 With the second term on the right-hand side zero in the case of the Theis
 situation, all net water flow into the ring goes into storage and, vice
 versa, all water extracted from the ring (i.e.
 from the aquifer) stems from storage and only from storage.
\end_layout

