\begin_layout Standard
In the derivation derived above, we considered a (semi-)confined aquifer,
 i.e.
 an aquifer filled to the top without a free water table.
 The storage coefficient, therefore is the elastic storage coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 [-], i.e.
 the specific storage coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{s}$
\end_inset

 [1/L] multiplied by the aquifer thickness 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 [L].
 If we substitute the specific yield 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

 [-], which is also dimensionless, for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 [-] the partial differential equation is just as valid for a water table
 aquifer, under the sole condition that the thickness of the water-table
 aquifer may be regarded constant, just like the transmissivity in the case
 of a confined or semi-confined aquifer.
 Generally, for this assumption to be acceptable, the drawdown due to the
 well extraction must not be too large with respect to the thickness of
 the aquifer.
 A drawdown below 20% of the wetted thickness of a water-table aquifer usually
 is acceptable, especially when we apply the linearization explained in
 the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Theis and Hantush well functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now with the governing partial differential equation in place, the art is
 to find closed analytical solutions for specific cases that are useful
 to us, for instance the flow towards wells.
 These solutions then must fulfill both the partial differential equation
 and the initial conditions and the boundary conditions.
 A useful solution of a well would be that for which the initial head or
 drawdown is zero, and as boundary conditions that the head at infinity
 will always remain zero, while the flow through a ring with infinitesimally
 small radius around the well equals the constant extraction from the well.
 This solution was found by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TheisC1935"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the Theis situation (i.e.
 without leakage) and by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hantush1955"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the Hantush situation (i.e.
 with leakage through an aquitard from an adjacent layer with constant head).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Theis solution is generally written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=h-h_{0}=\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\mbox{W}\left(u\right)\mbox{, with }u=\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}\left(-\right)$
\end_inset

 is called Theis' well function among hydrogeologists, see below.
 Note the small 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 [L] stands for change of head, while the big capital 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 [-] is used for the storage coefficient of the aquifer.
