\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that it is not the head that is important, only the difference from
 the initial head matters, which is the head change or the drawdown.
 Also notice that all steady-state well formulas have the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi kD$
\end_inset

, while the transient solutions all have the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi kD$
\end_inset

.
 Finally notice that the well function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}\left(\dots\right)$
\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 separately, but on a single variable, called 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, which combines 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 together with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $kD$
\end_inset

 in a specific way.
 All formulas describing transient flow to wells have this variable 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As just said, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 is known as Theis' well function among hydrologists.
 However, mathematicians new that function long before Theis; they have
 a name for it, namely the exponential integral, it can be expressed as
 an integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{W}\left(u\right)=\mbox{expint}\left(u\right)=\mbox{E}_{1}\left(u\right)=\intop_{u}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y}}{y}dy\label{eq:Theis-expint-representation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This well function is given in tables in books that describe pumping test
 analyses like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KrusemanG1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well as in books with mathematical tables like the famous 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Abramowitz1972"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Nowadays, this exponential integral function is readily available in software
 such as Python, but in Excel it has to be implemented by yourself, which
 may be done in Visual Basic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hantush solution function is similar, it can be expressed as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=h-h_{0}=\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\mathtt{W}_{h}\left(u,\frac{r}{\lambda}\right)\mbox{, with }u=\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt}\mbox{ and }\lambda=\sqrt{kDc}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}_{h}\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the Hantush well function, which now depends on both 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Mathematically, the Hantush well function is similar to to the Theis well
 function, it is written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{W}_{h}\left(u,\frac{r}{\lambda}\right)=\intop_{u}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y-\frac{\left(\frac{r}{2\lambda}\right)^{2}}{y}}}{y}dy\label{eq:Hantush-well-function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is immediately clear, that when 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, we get the Theis well function back.
 Hence, Theis is a special case of Hantush.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditions under which the drawdown formulas are valid are summarized
 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The aquifer has uniform transmissivity and uniform storativity (either elastic
 storativity (or storage coefficient) when confined/semi-confined, or specific
 yield when phreatic).
 In case of a phreatic/unconfined/water-table aquifer, the drawdown should
 be small with respect to the aquifer thickness so that the transmissivity
 is not changed much.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The aquifer extends to infinity.
 In practice, this means that the aquifer extends far enough such that the
 drawdown is not affected by boundaries of the groundwater system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The well is pumped at a constant rate from a given point in time, which
 is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 in the formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The diameter of the well is small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mahdi Hantush, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hantush1955"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, specified the conditions under which his solution is valid:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The non-steady drawdown distributed near a well discharging from an infinite
 leaky aquifer is presented.
 Variation of drawdown with time and distance caused by a well of constant
 discharge in confined sand of uniform thickness and uniform permeability
 is obtained.
 The discharge is supplied by the reduction of storage through expansion
 of the water and concomitant compression of the sand, and also by leakage
 through the confining bed.
 The leakage is assumed to be at a rate proportional to the drawdown at
 any point.
 Storage of water in the confining bed is neglected.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

