\begin_layout Subsection
Type-curves for the Theis and Hantush well functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All books on groundwater pumping tests show type curves for the Theis and
 Hantush well function (figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Theis-Hantush-type-curves"

\end_inset

).
 A type curve is a graph of the the well function plotted on double logarithmic
 scale in a way that makes it directly comparable with an actual drawdown
 curve versus time on double log axes.
 This is done by plotting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}\left(u\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}_{h}\left(u,\frac{r}{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 not versus 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 but versus 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u$
\end_inset

 on double log axes.
 The logic of doing this follows form 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u=\frac{4kDt}{r^{2}S}$
\end_inset

.
 The horizontal axis is then a constant times time, and so the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{W}\left(u\right)$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u$
\end_inset

 graph then gives a picture of drawdown versus time, which is definitely
 the easiest way to remember it.
 For the Hantush situation, we will have multiple type curves, each for
 a specific value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u$
\end_inset

 and, therefore of, small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t/r^{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 for small 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and large 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the Hantush well function behaves like the Theis well function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The type curves show that the Theis solution does not have a finite end-value;
 it keeps growing forever.
 Contrary to his, the Hantush curves all have a finite steady-state end-value,
 which depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\frac{r}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The higher the resistance of the aquitard, in fact the lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\frac{r}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, the later will the equilibrium be reached, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the Theis curve, being the limiting case when no equilibrium will ever
 be attained.
\end_layout

