\begin_layout Standard
In the past, these type curves have always been used to compute the drawdown.
 For instance say we want to compute the drawdown at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=250$
\end_inset

 m from the well after 
\begin_inset Formula $t=20$
\end_inset

 d of pumping at a rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=1200$
\end_inset

 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

/d.
 The formula is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\mbox{W}_{h}\left(u,\frac{r}{\lambda}\right),\,\,\,\,u=\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt},\,\,\,\,\lambda=\sqrt{kDc}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $kD=600$
\end_inset

 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/d, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0.2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1200$
\end_inset

 d, we then have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sqrt{600\times1200}=850$
\end_inset

 m and 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\frac{0.2}{4\times600}\frac{r^{2}}{t}=8.3\times10^{-5}\frac{r^{2}}{t}$
\end_inset

 then the drawdown at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=250$
\end_inset

 m after 20 days will follow from 
\begin_inset Formula $u=8.3\times10^{-5}\times\frac{250^{2}}{20}=0.259$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\frac{250}{850}=0.3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q/\left(4\pi kD\right)=1200/(4\pi600)=0.159$
\end_inset

, so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s & =0.159\times\mbox{W}_{h}\left(0.259,0.3\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{h}$
\end_inset

 can now be read from the type curve for 
\begin_inset Formula $r/\lambda=0.3$
\end_inset

.
 But on the horizontal axes we have to use 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u=3.86$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{h}\left(\frac{1}{u}=3.86,\frac{r}{\lambda}=0.3\right)\approx0.6$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the drawdown at 250 m from the well 20 days after pumping started
