\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Power-approximation-of-Theis-well-function"

\end_inset

Power approximation of Theis well function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next to its mathematical integral representation, the Theis well function
 given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Theis-expint-representation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the exponential integral can also be written as a power series (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KrusemanG1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathtt{\mbox{W}}\left(u\right) & = & -\gamma-\ln u+u-\frac{u^{2}}{2\times2!}+\frac{u^{3}}{3\times3!}-\frac{u^{4}}{4\times4!}+\dots\label{eq:Theis-power-series}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=0.577216\dots
\]

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the so-called
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Euler constant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is a fundamental mathematical constant much like 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, but only less well known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This power-series form of the Theis well function allows some simplifications,
 which prove extremely useful in practice, because it simplifies many an
 analysis and provides a useful characteristic expression like the
\emph on
 radius of influence
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for sufficiently small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, all the terms with the higher powers and even the term 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 will become negligible with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln u$
\end_inset

.
 Take for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $u=10^{-4},\,10^{-3},\,10^{-2},\,10^{-1},\,10^{0}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $-\ln u=9.4,\,6.9,\,4.6,\,2.3,\,0$
\end_inset

 which should make this clear.
 Hence, for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 less than about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\ln u$
\end_inset

 is less than 4% of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 When this is the case, we may approximate the well function to just the
 first two terms of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Theis-power-series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{W}\left(u\right) & \approx-\gamma-\ln u\\
 & \approx-0.577216-\ln\left(\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt}\right)\\
 & \approx\ln0.5614+\ln\left(\frac{4kDt}{r^{2}S}\right)\\
 & \approx\ln\left(\frac{2.25kDt}{r^{2}S}\right)\mbox{, with }u<0.1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, for small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, that is for very small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 or for very large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the Theis drawdown becomes a straight line when plotted versus 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $t/r^{2}$
\end_inset

