 Hence the extra drawdown between 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=10\tau$
\end_inset

 is the same whatever 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is small enough ( 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is large enough).
 The Theis type-curve on half-log axes already revealed that after some
 time the drawdown keeps increasing linearly with the log of time, i.e.
 with by a constant value for every log-cycle of time.
 But the approximation proves that this must indeed be the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radius of influence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Theis well function plotted versus 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $t/r^{2}$
\end_inset

 clearly shows that it takes some time for the drawdown to reach a piezometer
 at a given distance.
 Therefore, we may speak of a
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radius of influence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is dynamic, and indicates to how far from the well the drawdown
 is perceivable.
 It is often of practical importance.
 Clearly, we can define the radius of influence in different ways.
 For instance, we could say the radius of influence is the distance where
 the drawdown is 1 cm or, 10 cm or whatever seems appropriate.
 However, we could, and we do that here, opt for a more general definition.
 If we inspect the logarithmic approximation of the Theis well function,
 we see that at any given time, the drawdown is approximately a straight
 cone when plotted versus distance.
 Over time, the point of intersection of this straight cone with zero drawdown
 moves away from the well.
 It is natural to define the radius of influence to be the distance at which
 the straight drawdown line intersects the drawdown 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the log-approximation of the Theis well function, the analysis is straightf
orward.
 Starting with the approximation we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{W}\left(u\right)\approx\ln\left(\frac{2.25kDt}{r^{2}S}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

so that for this to be true, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log$
\end_inset

 must be 1.
 So,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2.25kDt}{r^{2}S}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this, we immediately obtain what may we call 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
the radius of influence
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\sqrt{\frac{2.25kDt}{S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the radius from the well at which the drawdown is still zero according
 to the approximate Theis well function.
 This radius is, therefore, proportional with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is, obviously, also larger when the transmissivity is larger, causing
 the well's influence to spread faster; and it is smaller when the storage
 coefficient is larger, which reduces the spreading of influence of the
 well.
 This simple expression is very practical to estimate how far the influence
 of a well under the conditions envisioned by Theis reaches as a function
 of time.
\end_layout

