\begin_layout Subsection
Relation between the transient Theis drawdown and the well-known Thiem solution
 for the drawdown in the steady-state situation.
 Time to reaching steady state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A steady-state situation will develop after some time when we have any fixed-hea
d boundary at some distance from the well.
 We can illustrate this using a negative mirror well at some distance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 from our well, which is equivalent to a straight line with a fixed head
 half-way and perpendicular to the line between the well and its mirror
 well.
 Superposition of these two wells yields (using the log-simplification for
 the Theis solution here for mathematical convenience):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=s_{1}+s_{2}=\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\ln\left(\frac{2.25kDt}{r_{1}^{2}S}\right)-\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\ln\left(\frac{2.25kDt}{r_{2}^{2}S}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the drawdown in the well, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{w}$
\end_inset

, the well's radius, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}=R$
\end_inset

, hence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s & =\frac{Q}{4\pi kD}\ln\left(\frac{R^{2}}{r_{w}^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{Q}{2\pi kD}\ln\left(\frac{R}{r_{w}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So if there is a fixed-head boundary somewhere, which in this case we created
 by putting a mirror well with opposite sign at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, this is equivalent to a well at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R/2$
\end_inset

 from a fully penetrating river.
 Adding a mirror well with opposite sign and the same absolute pumping rate,
 therefore, causes the drawdown to become constant after some time.
 This is true because the logarithmic approximation will always be valid
 after sufficiently long times.
 Also notice that the square under the logarithm leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi kD$
\end_inset

 (steady) instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi kD$
\end_inset

 (transient) in the numerator of the factor in front of the logarithm.
 This is always the case in steady-state solutions for wells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine after how much time the steady state is effectively reached
 is the same as determining after how much time the logarithmic simplification
 of the well function is valid over the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We may say as shown in before in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Power-approximation-of-Theis-well-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that this is the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t,R}<0.1$
\end_inset

.
 If we have for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $kD=600$
\end_inset

 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

/d and 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0.2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=200$
\end_inset

 m, then the time at which the steady state may be set to be effectively
 reached could be be estimated from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{R^{2}S}{4kDt} & =0.1\\
t & =\frac{1}{0.4}\frac{R^{2}S}{kD}=\frac{100^{2}\times0.2}{0.4\times600}=8.3d
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0.1$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary.
 Another also valid approach is through the argument at the steady state
 can only be reached after the
\emph on
radius of influence
\emph default
 has reached the mirror well.
 This approach gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\sqrt{\frac{2.25kD}{S}t}\rightarrow t_{ss}=\frac{R^{2}S}{2.25kD}=\frac{100^{2}\times0.2}{2.25\times600}=1.5d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Drawdown-vs-log-r-radius-of-influence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 it may be concluded that the time to reach steady state is, in fact, longer
 than the time for the radius of influence to reach the mirror well, about
 3 times as much seems a better value, which then yields 4.5 days.
 The best way would be to look at the Theis drawdown on linear scale versus
 1/u on log-scale (see figure  
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Theis-and-Hantush-curves-halflog-inflection-points"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to find that the drawdown on this graph as become straight at 
\begin_inset Formula $1/u\approx10$
\end_inset

 which is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $u\approx0.1$
\end_inset

, which is the same as our first estimate in this section and, therefore
 yields the best estimate for reaching the steady-state situation in this
 case.
 In conclusion, because the transition from transient to steady state is
 continuous, there is not exact point at which the steady state can be said
 to commence, but it is well possible to give a useful, well informed, quantitat
ive estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flow at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from the well in the Theis and Hantush situations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Theis situation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How much water is released from storage between two distances 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

? How much is the flow toward the well at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

? For such type of questions we need the flow in the aquifer at distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 For the Theis situation, we can determine this flow analytically, by taking
 the derivative of the drawdown with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 The derivation goes as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\frac{Q_{0}}{4\pi kD}\mathtt{\mbox{W}}\left(u\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Q_{r} & = & -2\pi rkD\frac{\partial s}{\partial r}\\
Q_{r} & = & -\left(2\pi rkD\right)\frac{\partial\left(\frac{Q_{0}}{4\pi kD}\mbox{W}\left(u\right)\right)}{\partial r}\\
 & = & -\frac{2\pi krD}{4\pi kD}Q_{0}\frac{d\mbox{W}\left(u\right)}{du}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Q_{r}}{Q_{0}}=-\frac{r}{2}\frac{d\mbox{W}\left(u\right)}{du}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $u=r^{2}S/\left(4kDt\right)$
\end_inset

 it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}=\frac{2rS}{4kDt}=\frac{2}{r}\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt}=\frac{2u}{r}
\]

\end_inset

hence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{Q_{r}}{Q_{0}} & = & -u\frac{d\mbox{W}\left(u\right)}{du}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the mathematical expression for the well function, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{Q_{r}}{Q_{0}} & = & -u\frac{d}{du}\left(\intop_{u}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y}}{y}dy\right)\\
 & = & +u\frac{e^{-u}}{u}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, finally, we obtain the simple analytical expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{Q_{r}}{Q_{0}} & = & e^{-u}\label{eq:Q-as-function-of-r-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Q_{r}}{Q_{0}}=\exp\left(-\frac{r^{2}S}{4kDt}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a very simple relationship between the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the constant extraction 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 from the well.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}$
\end_inset

, this ratio diminishes exponentially with the distance from the well.
 This means that the water comes from storage for say 99% within a given
 radius from the well.
 This radius is extending dynamically.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/t$
\end_inset

, it means that the ratio goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 within increasing time over any distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the flow becomes essentially steady, i.e.
 reaches for instance 99% of the total extraction rate within a given radius
 after a certain time.
 Within that radius, the discharge towards the well is essentially equal
 to the extraction from the well.
 Hence, over time, the water comes from the storage further and further
 from the well and the contribution from the zone closer to the well declines
 to zero over time.
 Although the drawdown will never become steady state in the Theis situation,
 the discharge at any fixed distance from the well does become essentially
 steady state (will approach the well extraction more and more over time).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A constant discharge equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 within a certain distance implies that the gradients will also become constant
 within the same distance.
 This in turn implies that the difference between the drawdowns in observation
 wells will also become constant and equal to the differences between the
 heads in these piezometers in the steady-state case, although this steady-state
 case is never reached.
 This implies that for sufficiently large times, we can then interpret the
 transient pumping test like we interpret a steady-state one, but based
 on the head differences between observation wells.
 Clearly, this requires the presence of sufficient observation.
 And, of course, one cannot obtain a storage coefficient from a steady-state
 analyses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By way of example, the drawdown and the accompanying ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}/Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q-as-function-of-r-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is shown graphically in figure  
