\begin_layout Subsection
Superposition in time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will illustrate superposition in time for the Theis situation, however,
 it works exactly the same for the Hantush case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A well may be switched on and off at will.
 The effect of this switching can be taken into account by superposition.
 For instance, a well that has been pumping for a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{i}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, after which it is switched off, can be viewed as two wells that pump continuou
sly.
 The first starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 with extraction 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the second at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\Delta t_{i}$
\end_inset

 with extraction 
\begin_inset Formula $-Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This way, the net extraction will be zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $t>t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 This superposition can be applied with a large number of changes of the
 flow rate at arbitrary times.
 The problem may only be that after many such changes one needs to carry
 on a large number of
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wells
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at the location of the real well to compute the current state.
 This is merely a computational burden, one that can be effectively dealt
 with through application of convolution, explained elsewhere in this syllabus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, we have for a well that switches on at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and then switches off at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=\frac{Q_{0}}{4\pi kD}\mbox{W}\left(u_{t-t_{0}}\right)-\frac{Q_{0}}{4\pi kD}\mbox{W}\left(u_{t-\left(t+\Delta t\right)}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where the second term is omitted al long as 
\begin_inset Formula $t<t_{0}+\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To deal with a well with varying extraction, we subdivide time in episodes
 during which the extraction from the well may be considered sufficiently
 constant.
 In this superposition we start a new well at the same position each time
 the flow rate changes.
 We let this new well extract the difference between the new rate and that
 of the previous well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, let the flow rate change at rate-change times 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},t_{3},\dots$
\end_inset

 after which the flow rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0},Q_{1},Q_{2},Q_{3},\dots$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We can simulate the heads by starting a new well at each of these rate-change
 times with extraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{0},\,Q_{1}-Q_{0},\,Q_{2}-Q_{1},\,Q_{3}-Q_{2},\dots
\]

\end_inset

because after 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 the total extraction is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

, after 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 ti is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}+Q_{1}-Q_{0}=Q_{1}$
\end_inset

, after 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 it is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}+Q_{2}-Q_{1}=Q_{2}$
\end_inset

 etc.
 Applying superposition then yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
