\begin_layout Standard
We can readily carry out a convolution in a spreadsheet or in Python.
 Python is more straightforward and flexible, therefore we'll use Python.
 To do convolution, we need input data, like a time series of the river
 water level and the impulse response (instantaneous pulse of zero-length
 but with given magnitude equal to 1) or block response block response (a
 pulse of of intensity 1 during a fixed time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

), i.e.
 the river level rises suddenly by 1 m and and falls again by 1 m after
 time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau$
\end_inset

, which will be the length of our time step.
 Working with the block response is easiest to comprehend, so we'll use
 that.
 When we have both the input and the block response, we have to carry out
 the convolution.
 The convolution for one time 
\emph on
t
\emph default
 is the past input up to time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, weighted by the block response reversed in time, that is we multiply the
 input at 
\begin_inset Formula $t-\tau$
\end_inset

 with the block-response value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Both the past input and the block response are entire arrays.
 So, the input array up to time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by the block-response array reversed in time to get the effect
 of all past input at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This is for one point in time, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 To get the result of the convolution for all times, we have to repeat this
 procedure for all times.
 What you notice, is, that convolution is in essence a moving weighted average
 of the input.
 The input is weighted by the reversed block response and for each time.
\end_layout

